{"version":1,"ops":[{"type":6,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609592660,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlRWRpdDo0NzQxMzQ3MjQ="},"target":"93d6e8fd7128e8fca59cfce0813108e6bb4d09c1df9c3aa73324933e3f74dbb6","message":"I've recently studied wyhash. Right now wyhash processes (\"mixes\") message bi-directionally (from start, and from end). While it does work as it is, passes SMHasher tests, its structure \"breaks\" on Permutation tests if the message is processed sequentially instead. As I'm developing PRVHASH myself, I've found similarities with wyhash - the functions are quite different, but have similar issues. This is the main reason I'm unable to increase its performance by a factor of 2 - this would require bi-directional processing, which makes streamed hashing impossible. (I'm not quite sure what's the purpose of high-speed hash function if it can't hash files in a streamed mode - I do not think anyone is going to keep multi-gigabyte files in memory).","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609592683,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlRWRpdDo0NzQxMzQ3Njg="},"target":"93d6e8fd7128e8fca59cfce0813108e6bb4d09c1df9c3aa73324933e3f74dbb6","message":"I've recently studied wyhash. Right now wyhash processes (\"mixes\") message bi-directionally (from start, and from end). While it does work as it is, passes SMHasher tests, its structure \"breaks\" on Permutation tests if the message is processed sequentially instead. As I'm developing PRVHASH myself, I've found similarities with wyhash - the functions are quite different, but have similar issues. This is the main reason I'm unable to increase its performance further by a factor of 2 - this would require bi-directional processing, which makes streamed hashing impossible. (I'm not quite sure what's the purpose of high-speed hash function if it can't hash files in a streamed mode - I do not think anyone is going to keep multi-gigabyte files in memory).","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609592786,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlRWRpdDo0NzQxMzQ4ODE="},"target":"93d6e8fd7128e8fca59cfce0813108e6bb4d09c1df9c3aa73324933e3f74dbb6","message":"I've recently studied wyhash. Right now wyhash processes (\"mixes\") message bi-directionally (from start, and from end). While it does work as it is, passes SMHasher tests, its structure \"breaks\" on Permutation tests if the message is processed sequentially instead. In sequential mode, the structure only allows mixing of a single 64-bit message word, otherwise correlations arise. As I'm developing PRVHASH myself, I've found similarities with wyhash - the functions are quite different, but have similar issues. This is the main reason I'm unable to increase its performance further by a factor of 2 - this would require bi-directional processing, which makes streamed hashing impossible. (I'm not quite sure what's the purpose of high-speed hash function if it can't hash files in a streamed mode - I do not think anyone is going to keep multi-gigabyte files in memory).","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609593092,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlRWRpdDo0NzQxMzUzNjQ="},"target":"93d6e8fd7128e8fca59cfce0813108e6bb4d09c1df9c3aa73324933e3f74dbb6","message":"I've recently studied wyhash. Right now wyhash processes (\"mixes\") message bi-directionally (from start, and from end). While it does work as it is, passes SMHasher tests, its structure \"breaks\" on Permutation tests if the message is processed sequentially instead. In sequential mode, the structure only allows mixing of a single 64-bit message word, if two 64-bit message words are mixed per round, correlations arise. As I'm developing PRVHASH myself, I've found similarities with wyhash - the functions are quite different, but have similar issues. This is the main reason I'm unable to increase its performance further by a factor of 2 - this would require bi-directional processing, which makes streamed hashing impossible. (I'm not quite sure what's the purpose of high-speed hash function if it can't hash files in a streamed mode - I do not think anyone is going to keep multi-gigabyte files in memory).","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609593120,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlRWRpdDo0NzQxMzU0MTc="},"target":"93d6e8fd7128e8fca59cfce0813108e6bb4d09c1df9c3aa73324933e3f74dbb6","message":"I've recently studied wyhash. Right now wyhash processes (\"mixes\") message bi-directionally (from start, and from end). While it does work as it is, passes SMHasher tests, its structure \"breaks\" on Permutation tests if the message is processed sequentially instead. In sequential mode, the structure only allows mixing of a single 64-bit message word, if two 64-bit message words are mixed per round, correlations arise. As I'm developing PRVHASH myself, I've found similarities with wyhash - the functions are quite different, but have similar issues. This is the main reason I'm unable to increase my function's performance further by a factor of 2 - this would require bi-directional processing, which makes streamed hashing impossible. (I'm not quite sure what's the purpose of high-speed hash function if it can't hash files in a streamed mode - I do not think anyone is going to keep multi-gigabyte files in memory).","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"cd39cff1d03b98b2a39748873893d10f390255ac"},"timestamp":1609593435,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ3MjU0MQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753472541"},"message":"@wangyi-fudan thoughts?","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"a8f5cc6e3ca5c3c08a52bd4ccf655efd7b4bcadf"},"timestamp":1609595190,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ3NTQ4NQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753475485"},"message":"bi-direction? how you get this feeling. wyhash is sequential from the begining to the end. when it reaches unaligned end, it finish it with a end-aligned read.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609595915,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ3Njk4MQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753476981"},"message":"\u003e bi-direction? how you get this feeling. wyhash is sequential from the begining to the end. when it reaches unaligned end, it finish it with a end-aligned read.\n\nI've meant such operations: `{ a=_wyr8(p); b=_wyr8(p+len-8); }`.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609596009,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ3NzE3OA==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753477178"},"message":"From my own tests, such construct fails with Permutation test: `seed=_wymix(_wyr8(p)^secret[1],_wyr8(p+8)^seed);`.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609596353,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ3NzcwNQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753477705"},"message":"@wangyi-fudan You are handling non-multiple of 8 buffer sizes rather originally, and maybe you are right with your approach. But technically you have data overlap the in some cases.","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609596353,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlQ29tbWVudEVkaXQ6NDI0MTE5MTIw"},"target":"9ecbec478400216570a4fd972fa65def8828a97b0eee83b375b2346cd8dfbe80","message":"@wangyi-fudan You are handling non-multiple of 8 buffer sizes rather originally, and maybe you are right with your approach. But technically you have data overlap in some cases.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"a8f5cc6e3ca5c3c08a52bd4ccf655efd7b4bcadf"},"timestamp":1609596570,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ3ODA1OQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753478059"},"message":"yes, there is data overlap. however, the overlaped data are XORed with different mask. so, actually, there is no problem","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609597257,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ3OTE0MA==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753479140"},"message":"\u003e yes, there is data overlap. however, the overlaped data are XORed with different mask. so, actually, there is no problem\n\nThere's one thing I've noted as well, what will happen if `i==4` here (and I assume this may happen if `len==60`):\n```\nwhile(_unlikely_(i\u003e16)){\tseed=_wymix(_wyr8(p)^secret[1],_wyr8(p+8)^seed);\ti-=16; p+=16;\t}\n    a=_wyr8(p+i-16); b=_wyr8(p+i-8);\n```\nWill it be a buffer overrun?","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"a8f5cc6e3ca5c3c08a52bd4ccf655efd7b4bcadf"},"timestamp":1609598017,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ4MDgyMw==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753480823"},"message":"since this code happed in len\u003e16 branch. it is safe to back-read 16 bytes.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609598174,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ4MTEyNA==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753481124"},"message":"\u003e since this code happed in len\u003e16 branch. it is safe to back-read 16 bytes.\n\n`b=_wyr8(p+i-8);` will overrun if `i==4`.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609599954,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ4NDQzNQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753484435"},"message":"As far as my original post is concerned, more specifically, correlations may be detected in wyhash-like structure if elements of the Permutation data set are appended with zeroes, so that the hash function runs for several \"idle\" rounds. At least it was so in my tests, I may be wrong, of course.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609602646,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ4OTE0Nw==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753489147"},"message":"The reason wyhash-like structures are problematic is that they perform \"compression\" after multiplication: `m=A*B; return m^m\u003e\u003e64`. Loss of state information.","files":null},{"type":6,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609602646,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlQ29tbWVudEVkaXQ6NDI0MTI0NTk1"},"target":"973577ee4a82427d225f9c809d706445c9a244419f28f3bf2b93724e96dee886","message":"The reason wyhash-like structures are problematic is that they perform \"compression\" after multiplication: `m=A*B; return m^m\u003e\u003e64`. Loss of state information. They work great only if input has the same length as state variable: in this case the provided entropy is dispersed back almost completely, but still is subject to occassional loss, especially apparent with 16-bit state variables.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"a8f5cc6e3ca5c3c08a52bd4ccf655efd7b4bcadf"},"timestamp":1609602676,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ4OTQzMg==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753489432"},"message":"the problem of wyhash is that it has no problem ;-)","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609602862,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzQ4OTc1OQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753489759"},"message":"\u003e the problem of wyhash is that it has no problem ;-)\n\nWell, maybe, as you wish. Anyway, it's not usable for file hashing in its current form. Strangely enough, Reini Urban advertises fast hash functions as useful for file hashing without even checking if they have the necessary interface.","files":null},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609671154,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1MzU5OTA0Mg==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-753599042"},"message":"I'm closing this topic. Sorry for disturbance. Maybe 128-bit multiplication does allow to mix two 64-bit messages, need to do more tests.","files":null},{"type":4,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609671154,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDExOkNsb3NlZEV2ZW50NDE2MjM1NDI2Ng=="},"status":2},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"1840e3905256ae05a0d1ed3fdecefe41fac4d5a7"},"timestamp":1609776225,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDc1NDA2MTQxMQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/177#issuecomment-754061411"},"message":"Anyway, from the point of view of \"message shuffling\", a construct like `m=A*B; return m^m\u003e\u003e64` used in wyhash is not ideal. You may compare it to my inner shuffler which produces an ideal remapping without holes. For certain, if 2 message words will be shuffled, it will be a complete loss of information.\n```\n#include \u003cstdio.h\u003e\n#include \u003cstdint.h\u003e\n\nconst int shuf_bits = 10;\nconst int shuf = 1 \u003c\u003c shuf_bits;\nconst int mask = shuf - 1;\n\nuint32_t mulfn( uint32_t Seed, uint32_t Seed2, uint32_t m )\n{\n/*\tSeed2 ^= m;\n\tSeed += Seed2;\n\tSeed \u0026= mask;\n\tSeed *= ( Seed2 - ~Seed2 ) \u0026 mask;\n*/\n\tuint32_t mv = Seed ^ m;\n\tmv *= Seed2;\n\tSeed = mv ^ mv \u003e\u003e shuf_bits;\n\n\treturn( Seed \u0026 mask );\n}\n\nint main()\n{\n\tuint64_t HitCount = 0;\n\tuint32_t Seed;\n\tuint32_t Seed2;\n\tuint32_t m;\n\n\tfor( Seed = 0; Seed \u003c shuf; Seed++ )\n\t{\n\t\tfor( Seed2 = 0; Seed2 \u003c shuf; Seed2++ )\n\t\t{\n\t\t\tuint8_t HitBuf[ shuf ] = { 0 };\n\n\t\t\tfor( m = 0; m \u003c shuf; m++ )\n\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\tuint32_t v = mulfn( Seed, Seed2, m );\n\n\t\t\t\tif( HitBuf[ v ] == 0 )\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\tHitBuf[ v ] = 1;\n\t\t\t\t\tHitCount++;\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\n\tprintf( \"Hits: %llu/%llu\\n\", HitCount, (uint64_t) shuf * shuf * shuf );\n}\n```","files":null}]}